Title:
Fantastic unwind information and where to find them (BYOUD ÔÇô Bring Your Own Unwinding Data)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4ÔÇô8 sentences max):
- This post introduces BYOUD, a CET-compliant call stack spoofing framework that avoids modifying return addresses (which Intel CET shadow stacks would detect) by instead manipulating Windows x64 unwind metadata.  
- It targets the separation between CETÔÇÖs return-flow integrity (shadow stack) and Windows stack walking/unwinding (SEH + `.pdata`/`UNWIND_INFO`) to make stack traces appear legitimate and fully unwindable while hiding real caller frames.  
- Multiple variants are described: direct tampering of `UNWIND_INFO`, hijacking `RUNTIME_FUNCTION` unwind offsets, injecting/reusing runtime function entries, and a JIT-oriented approach using `RtlAddFunctionTable`.  
- The post also dives into practical constraints and artifacts, including interactions with `/GS` stack cookies and why `dbghelp`/`StackWalk64` can fail to consult dynamic function tables depending on address ownership.  
- It proposes a more complex ÔÇťstate-drivenÔÇŁ architecture to better align visible stacks with shadow stack reality, and discusses detection strategies (integrity monitoring of exception metadata, shadow stack vs. normal stack comparison).  
- Useful for red teamers/malware developers researching post-CET evasion and for blue teamers building detections around unwind metadata tampering and shadow stack validation.

Technical Focus:
- Intel CET / Hardware-enforced Shadow Stack (HSP) constraints on stack spoofing  
- Windows x64 unwinding internals: `.pdata`, `RUNTIME_FUNCTION`, `UNWIND_INFO`, unwind opcodes (`UWOP_ALLOC_SMALL/LARGE`)  
- Metadata tampering and runtime function table manipulation (offset hijacking, injection, reuse)  
- Dynamic function tables for JIT code: `RtlAddFunctionTable` / `RtlDeleteFunctionTable` and lookup paths  
- Stack walking discrepancies: `RtlVirtualUnwind`/`RtlLookupFunctionEntry` vs `dbghelp` (`StackWalk64`, `SymFunctionTableAccess64`)  
- Detection approaches: section integrity checks, memory protection monitoring, shadow stack correlation

Use Cases:
- Hide in-memory execution/shellcode frames from user-mode stack walkers without tripping CET
- Build CET-compatible proxy-call based stack spoofing for API invocation (e.g., via RPC proxy functions)
- Research and validate how EDRs/tools reconstruct stacks (OS unwinder vs dbghelp pipeline)
- Develop detections for `.pdata`/unwind metadata tampering and suspicious dynamic function tables
- Create PoCs to test shadow stack vs normal stack inconsistency detection

Keywords:
Intel CET, Hardware Stack Protection, shadow stack, Control Protection Exception, Windows x64 unwinding, SEH, .pdata, .xdata, RUNTIME_FUNCTION, UNWIND_INFO, UNWIND_CODE, UWOP_ALLOC_LARGE, BaseThreadInitThunk, RtlUserThreadStart, RtlVirtualUnwind, RtlLookupFunctionEntry, RtlAddFunctionTable, StackWalk64, dbghelp.dll, SymFunctionTableAccess64, stack spoofing, call stack evasion